{"key":"post-4988029","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>4988029</id>\n<content>That's from running your stove too hot.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Once the weight begins to rattle, turn down the stove so the weight stops rattling, but a very small amount of steam constantly escapes.  The steam will begin to vent from under the weight at about 14 lbs.  Find the setting on your stove that will keep the steam venting without actually rattling the weight more than once or twice a minute.  Used like that, you will only use about 1/4 to 1/2 cup of water during a two hour cycle.  It's also important to let steam vent freely for five to ten minutes before you put the weight on to build pressure.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The lids on the late model AA have two holes tapped for 1/8&quot; NPT.  &lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>4988170</next>\n<prev>4987186</prev>\n<first>4984923</first>\n<last>4992286</last>\n<when>1133154380</when>\n<utime>11/28/05 07:06 AM</utime>\n</post>"}